<P ID="4"><ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Council</ENAMEX> approves interlocal agreement with <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Bellevue</ENAMEX>
This <TIMEX TYPE="DATE">past Monday</TIMEX> <TIMEX TYPE="TIME">night</TIMEX>, the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Alderwood</ENAMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">City Council</ENAMEX> approved an interlocal agreement with the <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">City of Bellevue</ENAMEX> for the purchase of city supplies.
<ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Alderwood</ENAMEX> <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">City</ENAMEX> Manager <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Tom Rockford</ENAMEX> said <ENAMEX TYPE="LOCATION">Bellevue</ENAMEX> officials approached the city about joining a group of other cities that would be able to bid on supplies and services.
"It does not bind us," said <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Rockford</ENAMEX>. "It simply is an opportunity."
<ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Councilman Tom Seeger</ENAMEX> thought the idea <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Rockford</ENAMEX> presented was outstanding, but wanted to keep local merchants in mind first as long as they were within <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">5 percent</NUMEX> of the asking price.
The <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Council</ENAMEX> agreed with <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Seeger</ENAMEX>'s suggestion and asked city staff to keep local merchants in mind when looking at supply orders. Mayor <ENAMEX TYPE="PERSON">Rex Luthor</ENAMEX> reminded <ENAMEX TYPE="ORGANIZATION">Council</ENAMEX> that <NUMEX TYPE="PERCENT">1 percent</NUMEX> of all sales tax revenue goes back into city coffers.
</P> 


 




